{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3be58a23-4a7b-4434-936d-8c63d78fa1f1","content":"This question is about general .NET/NativeAOT knowledge rather than something documented in this repository. Here's the answer:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS will write a `core.<pid>` file to `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it. You may also need:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (since NativeAOT produces native binaries):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively**, check **Console.app → Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports under `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`.\n\nKey difference from CoreCLR: NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`, so you rely on the OS-level core dump mechanism or macOS crash reports instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ba040ae0-cd91-4ff2-ab2a-bfbba60f1444","outputTokens":327,"requestId":"7643:2A4A94:1AA6BBD:1E3A626:69FE9304"},"id":"23848bf1-8e6b-49e5-aa08-6c8126fbfd13","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:51:09.297Z","parentId":"99ab2701-71e9-4f87-86b9-ec4c87462b1b"}
